# Call UDFs asynchronously

Designing workflows to handle asynchronous tasks makes them more responsive, scalable,
and resilient to errors. To query a large dataset, you can use Fused to run spatially
filtered tasks in parallel and stitch the results at the end.

This example shows how to create a GeoDataFrame of Overture Buildings by calling the UDF
in parallel.

To run it, first add the Overture UDF to your Fused Workbench account, then create a
token for it.

Then define a polygon for the area of interest. The code below will use the
[mercantile](https://mercantile.readthedocs.io/en/stable/api/mercantile.html) Python
library to determine the tiles that cover the polygon, then call the UDF for each tile.

import asyncio
import fused
import mercantile
from shapely.geometry import Polygon
from concurrent.futures import ThreadPoolExecutor
import pandas as pd
import nest_asyncio

# Enable nested asyncio event loops in notebook
nest_asyncio.apply()

# Define your downstream UDF
async def process_tile(tile):
    # Place signed UDF token for Overture UDF here
    token = "55ffe996fc2bd635cde3beda7e2632005e228798a1ef333297240b86af7d12a4"
    # Run UDF
    return await fused.run(token, x=tile.x, y=tile.y, z=tile.z, sync=False)

# Define the coordinates of the bounding box for Ohio
import geopandas as gpd

# Polygon encompassing SF
gdf = gpd.GeoDataFrame.from_features({"type":"FeatureCollection","features":[{"type":"Feature","properties":{},"geometry":{"type":"Polygon","coordinates":[[[-122.51127752527577,37.77965912317954],[-122.51037898525577,37.76989324418009],[-122.47041528630982,37.77191514041022],[-122.47059572773038,37.782048841548836],[-122.51127752527577,37.77965912317954]]]}}]})

# Determine the tiles covering the polygon
tiles = list(mercantile.tiles(*gdf.geometry.iloc[0].bounds, zooms=15))  # Adjust zoom level as needed

# Define a function to process each tile in parallel
async def process_tiles_parallel(tiles):
    dfs = []
    with ThreadPoolExecutor(max_workers=5) as executor:  # Adjust max_workers as needed
        loop = asyncio.get_event_loop()
        futures = [loop.run_in_executor(executor, process_tile, tile) for tile in tiles]
        for future in await asyncio.gather(*futures):
            dfs.append(await future)
    return dfs

# Process the tiles in parallel and concatenate the results
async def main():
    dfs = await process_tiles_parallel(tiles)
    return pd.concat(dfs, ignore_index=True)

# Run the asynchronous function
out = asyncio.run(main())
